<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="142" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d142">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A3/1864</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Japanese Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Saito</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 291</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-29">December 29,
                                1936</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor, under instructions from
                            my Government, to communicate to you the following:— <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>In response to the invocation of Article 21 of the London Naval
                                    Treaty of 1930 by the British Government to retain five
                                    subcategory (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) cruisers, namely the <hi rend="italic">Cardiff, Ceres, Caledon, Calypso</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Caradoc</hi>, the Government of Japan has
                                    decided to retain the <hi rend="italic">Tsushima</hi> (3,120
                                    tons), one of the subcategory (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)
                                    cruisers which are, under the Treaty above referred to, to be
                                    disposed of before the end of this year.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hirosi Saito</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>